{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17590549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17590549"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:48:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:48:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21266"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21266"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.64,0.03,0.12,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99794"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14139"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1989"},{"type":"tags","id":"1993"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4489"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"8274"},{"type":"tags","id":"11539"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34395"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99794"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA nine-year-old Aboriginal boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of puffy eyes and face, particularly noticeable in the mornings. His mother reports that his urine appears dark. Two weeks ago, he had a sore throat that resolved without treatment. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly unwell with periorbital and facial oedema. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. There is mild pitting oedema of the ankles. Throat examination reveals no erythema or exudate. Urinalysis shows 3+ blood, 2+ protein, and specific gravity 1.025.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24-hour urine protein collection","Anti-streptolysin O titre","Throat swab culture","Complement C3 and C4 levels","Renal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis (APSGN): oedema, hypertension, and haematuria. The timing of symptoms approximately two weeks after a sore throat is consistent with APSGN following streptococcal pharyngitis. APSGN is an immune complex-mediated disease that occurs following infection with nephritogenic strains of Group A Streptococcus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-streptolysin O titre\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation as it provides evidence of recent streptococcal infection. ASO titres begin to rise approximately one week after streptococcal infection and peak at 3-5 weeks. A positive ASO titre in the context of this clinical presentation would strongly support the diagnosis of APSGN. Anti-DNase B is another serological marker that can be used, particularly in cases following skin infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement C3 and C4 levels\u003C/strong\u003E would also be useful in the diagnostic workup of APSGN, as low C3 levels are characteristic of the disease (with normal C4 levels). However, establishing evidence of recent streptococcal infection is the priority for diagnosis, making ASO titre the most appropriate next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically necessary for the initial diagnosis of APSGN. While it may show enlarged, echogenic kidneys, these findings are non-specific and would not confirm the diagnosis. Renal ultrasound would be more appropriate if there were concerns about other causes of acute kidney injury or if the clinical course was atypical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThroat swab culture\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be positive at this stage, as the streptococcal pharyngitis typically precedes APSGN by 1-2 weeks. By the time nephritis develops, the throat infection has often resolved, as appears to be the case in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urine protein collection\u003C/strong\u003E would provide quantification of proteinuria but is not necessary for the initial diagnosis of APSGN. The urinalysis already demonstrates proteinuria, and while nephrotic-range proteinuria can occur in APSGN, establishing the link to streptococcal infection is more diagnostically valuable at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of APSGN typically involves supportive care, including salt and fluid restriction if oedema is present, and antihypertensive therapy if blood pressure remains elevated. Antibiotics are recommended to eradicate any remaining streptococcal infection, even if cultures are negative. Most children with APSGN have an excellent prognosis with complete recovery, although a small percentage may develop chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis typically presents with oedema, hypertension, and haematuria approximately 1-4 weeks after streptococcal infection.","Urinalysis showing haematuria, proteinuria, and red cell casts is characteristic of acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis.","Elevated anti-streptolysin O (ASO) or anti-DNase B titres confirm recent streptococcal infection in suspected acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis."],"references":["Singh\u00a0J, Hempenstall\u00a0A, Scrace\u00a0M, Craig\u00a0L, McDonald\u00a0M. A refresher on the primary care and public health management of acute post\u2011streptococcal glomerulonephritis. Aust\u00a0J\u00a0Gen\u00a0Pract.\u00a02025;54(4):213\u2011217\u00a0Available\u00a0at:\u00a0https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2025/april/a-refresher-on-the-primary-care-and-public-health"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82179"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21266"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82179"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-22T10:38:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-24T18:39:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14139"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99794"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a